In this statement, President Obama expresses his condolences on the passing of Nobel Laureate Gabriel García Márquez, whom he considers one of the greatest visionary writers and one of his personal favorites. He refers to Márquez affectionately as "Gabo" and highlights his international recognition for his masterpiece, One Hundred Years of Solitude. The President recalls meeting Márquez in Mexico, where he received an inscribed copy of his book. He acknowledges Márquez's role as a representative and voice for the people of the Americas, as well as his influence in inspiring others to write. The President offers his thoughts to Márquez's family and friends, assuring them that his work will continue to be cherished for generations to come.